## Abstract Classes

A class that is too general is called an abstract class

* An abstract class cannot be used to create objects. An abstract class can contain abstract functions, which are implemented in concrete derived classes
* In C++, abstract functions are called
* You cannot make an object of the class because it is too vague to be defined

    virtual double getArea() = 0;

### Notes

* If you derive from an abstract class and don't override, the child will still be an abstract class.
* Object should be passed by reference or a pointer, if it's passed by value it won't work.